        <body>       
                
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Jewish Foster Home<lb/>
                AND<lb/>
                Orphan Asylum&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>S. M. FLEISCHMAN&#44; SUPT.<lb/></p>
            <p>Germantown&#44; Phila.&#44; April 27<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1887.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Mr. Morais.<lb/></p>
            <p>Phila.		My dear sir &#38; friend&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I regret exceedingly<lb/> that the &#34;hurry and worry&#34; incident to an<lb/> <sic>ocasion</sic> such as the &#34;Annual Meeting&#34; last<lb/> Sunday prevented me from expressing to<lb/> you personally my heartfelt thanks for<lb/> your kind words spoken at the meeting.<lb/>  The general approbation with which they<lb/> were received is a fair index of their worth&#44;<lb/> but to me and my assistants they are of still<lb/> greater value since they are a source of much<lb/> encouragement to us and a great support<lb/> from the public.  Encouraged and<lb/> supported by such sentiments&#44; voiced by<lb/> one who in so eminent a degree represents<lb/> the honest and benevolent spirit of our<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Jewish Foster Home<lb/>
                AND<lb/>
                Orphan Asylum&#44;<lb/>
                S. M. FLEISCHMAN&#44; SUPT.<lb/></p>
            <p>Germantown&#44; Phila.&#44; 188<lb/></p>
            <p>people irrespective of religious differences&#44;<lb/> we shall cheerfully continue to discharge<lb/> our sacred duties&#44; constantly aiming to make<lb/> our &#34;Home&#34; in every respect an ideal one.<lb/>  You will please pardon the superscription&#44;<lb/> but I feel that one so kindly disposed towards<lb/> us&#44; can be nothing less than a <hi rend="underline">friend</hi>.  Mrs.<lb/> Fleischman and Miss Amelia wish to be<lb/> kindly remembered.  Very gratefully yours<lb/> S. M. Fleischman.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
